1 2. [does not permit a user to play more than 54 bingo cards
2 at the same time;
3 3.] does not randomly generate any numbers; and
4 [4.] 3. is not part of an integrated system;
5 (v) is used by the State Lottery and Gaming Control Commission
6 under Title 9 of the State Government Article;
7 (vi) if legislation takes effect authorizing the operation of video
8 lottery terminals, is a video lottery terminal as defined in and licensed under that
9 legislation;
10 (vii) is a skills–based amusement device that awards prizes,
11 merchandise, tickets, tokens, or other objects that:
12 1. per play, do not exceed minimal value approved by the
13 State Lottery and Gaming Control Commission through regulation; and
14 2. may be accumulated and exchanged for noncash
15 merchandise or prizes of value that:
16 A. is similar to the cumulated value of the objects exchanged;
17 and
18 B. does not exceed a minimal wholesale value of $599; or
19 (viii) is a skills–based device that awards noncash merchandise and is
20 located at a family entertainment center in Worcester County licensed under § 9–1B–02 of
21 the State Government Article.
22 12–301.1.
23 (e) (1) THIS SUBSECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO AN ELECTRONIC INSTANT
24 BINGO MACHINE AUTHORIZED UNDER § 12–308 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
25 (2) An electronic gaming device that is not licensed or otherwise operated
26 in compliance with the provisions of this section as of January 1, 2013, is an illegal gaming
27 device that may not legally operate in the State.
28 12–308.
29 (A) Notwithstanding any other provisions of this subtitle, an entity licensed to
30 offer instant bingo under a commercial bingo license on July 1, 2007, or by a qualified
31 organization as defined in § 13–201 of this article on the premises of the qualified

4 HOUSE BILL 1587
1 organization may continue to operate a game of instant bingo in the same manner using
2 electronic machines, provided that:
3 (1) [(i) the machines were in operation for a 1–year period ending
4 December 31, 2007; or
5 (ii) the machines were in operation under a commercial bingo license
6 on December 31, 2007;
7 (2)] the entity does not operate more than TWICE the number of electronic
8 machines in operation on February 28, 2008; and
9 [(3)] (2) the conduct of the gaming and operation of the machines are
10 consistent with all other provisions of this article.
11 (B) AN ELECTRONIC MACHINE ALLOWED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS
12 SECTION IS NOT REQUIRED TO PRINT A PAPER TICKET FOR EACH GAME OF INSTANT
13 BINGO PLAYED UNLESS THE PLAYER ELECTS TO PRINT THE TICKET.
14 (C) THE STATE LOTTERY AND GAMING CONTROL COMMISSION SHALL
15 ADOPT REGULATIONS TO IMPLEMENT THIS SECTION.
16 Chapter 603 of the Acts of 2012
17 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, a licensee or organization
18 that is authorized under State law to own or operate electronic bingo machines for use after
19 July 1, 2012, may repair and replace the authorized electronic bingo machines provided
20 that the machines operate in the same manner as those in operation by the same
21 organization as of February 28, 2008[, and that the organization does not operate more
22 than the number of electronic bingo machines in operation as of February 28, 2008].
23 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
24 1, 2026.

